text: @dr_fcalderaibd @MondayNightIBD @abbvie @JanssenUS So Freddy: “m” in mRNA stands for messenger RNA - > delivers a message to the cell to produce a protein of the virus - our immune system can be activated & if exposed to the “real virus” be ready to defend the body ! mRNA doesn’t stay in our body & gets destroyed after few days.
name: Aline Charabaty, M.D.

text: @DCharabaty @MondayNightIBD @abbvie @JanssenUS 2) Although no mRNA vaccines against other infectious agents are presently available, mRNA vaccines have shown great promise, and in recent years many are in development to treat cancer and other infectious disease such as Zika virus and cytomegalovirus.
name: Freddy Caldera, DO, MS

text: @DCharabaty @MondayNightIBD @abbvie @JanssenUS 1) The vaccine antigen is coded by mRNA, which is protected by a lipoprotein coat. Upon vaccine administration, cells pick up the mRNA and translate it into a protein (in this case, the SARS-CoV2 spike protein). The immune system then mounts a response to that protein.
name: Freddy Caldera, DO, MS
